AB  - The traditional maintenance mode of hydropower equipment relies on regular inspection and post-fault processing, which has problems such as large unplanned downtime losses and sudden failure risks of key components. In order to shift to predictive maintenance, this study aims to identify the degradation status of equipment in advance through machine learning algorithms. The specific methods include: deploying multi-source sensors such as vibration, temperature, and oil to collect equipment operation data in real time; performing wavelet packet decomposition on the original data to eliminate noise and extract time-frequency domain features; using Recursive Feature Elimination (RFE) to screen out 15 key degradation features; building a prediction model based on the fusion of eXtreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost) and Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM), in which XGBoost processes static features and LSTM captures the time series dependency of vibration signals; applying transfer learning to adapt the 700MW unit training model to the 300MW unit. In the two-year operation data verification of 12 units in three hydropower stations, the model's bearing fault warning accuracy reaches 98.5%, with a false alarm rate of only 3.5%. Among 15 fault predictions, 14 are successfully predicted in advance, and the annual comprehensive maintenance cost is reduced by 22.8%. This solution proves that machine learning can achieve early and accurate prediction of hydropower equipment failures, and promote the maintenance strategy from "periodic maintenance" to "state-driven".
ER  - 

