AB  - Early fault diagnosis of rotor and stator windings in wound-field synchronous generators (WFSGs) is very important for maintenance plans and preventing production losses of hydropower plants. Existing methods of detecting winding faults in electrical machines mainly rely on current signals. However, installing current sensors in many decadesold WFSGs might not be feasible. This study presents applied signal processing methods and a data-driven model to classify multiple winding faults using vibration signals alone, which can be easily installed outside WFSGs as a plug-N-play solution. The vibration data is collected from an in-house experimental setup of two WFSGs. Feature extraction was performed using the wavelet scattering transform (WST). Expert knowledge-based frequency features were also extracted from the fast Fourier transform (FFT) spectrum and combined with the WST features to improve fault sensitivity. Several machine learning algorithms were evaluated along with the proposed method to investigate the performance across all fault categories.
ER  - 

